canonical:
  title: 潭上有感
  author: 金時習
  language: lzh
  text: 峯上靑楓千萬枝傷春情緖亂如絲岩花灼灼應無主胡蝶雙雙亦可悲人事那能如水鏡烏雛誰復識雄雌秦坑漢錮皆如此孰是眞吹孰竊吹
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 潭上有感
  author: 金時習
  language: lzh
  text: 峯上靑楓千萬枝。傷春情緖亂如絲。岩花灼灼應無主。胡蝶雙雙亦可悲。人事那能如水鏡。烏雛誰復識雄雌。秦坑漢錮皆如此。孰是眞吹孰竊吹。
korean:
  title: 담상 유감
  author: 김시습
  language: kor
  text: |-
    봉우리 위의 푸른 단풍나무는 천만 가지인데
    봄을 슬퍼하는 정서는 어지럽기 실과 같도다
    바위 곁에 핀 꽃 울긋불긋하여도 응당 주인은 없으리니
    나는 나비 쌍쌍으로 가는 것 슬퍼할 만도 하여라
    어떻게 하면 사람의 일이 수경같을꼬
    까마귀 새끼의 수컷 암컷을 그 누가 분별하리
    진나라의 구덩이와 한나라의 금고가 다 이러하거니
    부는 것 어느 것이 참이요 어느 것이 거짓인가
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1430_010_0880&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 수경(水鏡) : '
    value: 물은 가만히 있으면 맑아지고 거울도 닦으면 밝아지므로 그같이 맑고 밝을 수 있는가 하는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 진(秦)나라의 …… 이러하거니 : '
    value: 진(秦)나라에서는 선비들이 소용없이 떠들기만 한다 하여 큰 구덩이를 파고 460여 명의 선비들을 산채로 쓸어 묻었었다. 한나라 말년에는 선비들이 나라의 정치를 논평한다고 수백명의 명사들을 모두 금고형(禁錮刑)에 처하였었다.
english:
  title: Reflections by the Pool
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten thousand branches of green maple crown the peak,
    and spring's sorrow tangles through my heart like thread.
    Flowers blaze bright against the stone, yet have no master—
    even the paired butterflies that drift past seem worthy of tears.

    How can the affairs of men ever mirror still water's clarity?
    Who can now distinguish the raven's chick, male from female?
    Qin's pit and Han's imprisonment came to this very thing—
    which is true flute-playing, and which mere theft of the sound?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of water mirror refers to the classical ideal that stillness and clarity go hand in hand—like water that becomes clear when undisturbed, or a mirror that shines when polished. The poet questions whether human affairs can ever achieve such purity.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Qin''s pit and Han''s imprisonment: During China''s Qin Dynasty, scholars were buried alive en masse in great pits for their useless talk. In late Han, hundreds of renowned scholars were imprisoned under prohibitive law when they dared comment on state affairs. The poet invokes these historical atrocities to suggest that the distinction between truth and falsehood, between authentic and counterfeit, remains as murky as it ever was.'
  - key: ''
    value: The distinction between male and female raven chicks echoes an ancient Confucian text, signifying the difficulty of knowing true nature or proper distinction in a disordered world.
